Short summary: Configuration was erased because the AWS managed server went down. We had to restore the configuration to make it work again.

Root Cause: The Redis (in-memory DB) node physically went down on the AWS side. It was automatically re-created but the data in the new instance was not restored. (These are circumstances we need to consult AWS on why they happened)

Since the Redis was empty, services that relied on it started to fail. Initially, this included Login, and therefore all App services were inaccesible. The login flow expects the data (token) to be purged/refreshed regularly (Time to Live is 30 minutes) so within less than an hour, it wrote a fresh set of data back to Redis which allowed users to be able to login again without a remediative action from our end other than lifting the Maintenance Page. However, other microservices (transfer-service -> vision service -> config-server) for P2P and Fund services also use config data stored in Redis. Since the data was missing with no mechanism to automatically repopulate them, then those services remained non-functional until we figured it out and restored the data.

Key learnings and adjustment we will make:
1. For In-memory DBs (Redis), we will add a new alarm conditional for DB utilization dropping below 2%. This is an indicator that the In-memory DB was flushed.
2. We will have MTC domain teams review all services that are using In-memory DBs to ensure that there are full-proof mechanisms to read and load back into the In-memory DB an updated file of the data content upon node failure and re-creation.
